observations.recommendation:
We recommended that the Local Executive:

enjoin all Department Heads concerned to adopt and follow the procedures set under the LRAMM prescribed by the DILG and eventual compliance with the requirements on reporting prescribed under COA Circular 2015-008;

prior to the preparation of the property records by the Accounting and the Property/Supply Department, review the requirements of COA Circular 2020-006 as mentioned above, on the one-time cleansing of PPEs, in order to have a verifiable data of it as to existence, condition and accountability.

We also reiterated that the Local Executive initiate/facilitate the disposal of unserviceable properties in accordance with the procedures mentioned above;

instruct the Acting Municipal Accountant to 

continue its compliance with the preparation and maintenance of Property Ledger Cards; 

(ii) keep and maintain subsidiary records for roads and road components tor every road network; and 

(iii) prepare a lapsing schedule for the computation of the depreciation tor each component at the end of the year; and

(b) advise the General Services Officer to 

(i) comply with the preparation and maintenance of Property Cards; 

(ii) prepare an Inventory and Inspection Report of Unserviceable Property and Report of Waste Materials, where applicable, for properties and request the same for disposal; 

(iii) facilitate the conversion of vehicles with green plates to red plates and follow-up with concerned agencies the availability of government plates for newly acquired service vehicles.

We reiterated and made further recommendations and Management agreed that the Local Chief Executive:

direct the MPDO 

(i) to submit a revised AIP as called for by the above-defined regulations; 

(ii) henceforth, check/monitor if actual projects undertaken from the fund are in harmony with the approved AIP; 

(iii) coordinate efforts with the BAC members and Municipal Engineer to properly plan and schedule all procurement activities and conduct regular monitoring of the status of project implementation so that necessary interventions may be introduced at the earliest time to give way for their timely completion; and 

(iv) exclude ineligible charges to the fund as cited above; 

instruct the BAC to consider early procurement activities prior to the approval of the appropriation short of award, in order to facilitate the required bidding and other procurement activities on time; and

advise the MBO Budget officer, for the inclusion of an allotment for those ineligible charges made under the fund to MOOE, in order to comply with the objectives of the fund.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive:

if budget permits, purchase the required CBMS and the training on the usage thereof; 

instruct the Municipal Budget Officer and the GFPP to monitor/ensure that the GAD budget is at least 5% of the total budget, as called for under the above-mentioned regulations;

require the Municipal Planning and Development Officer (MPDO), in coordination with the GAD Focal Point Person (GFPP), to work on the establishment of a GAD database and the maintenance thereof for a more gender-responsive planning, programming and policy formulation; and

require the GFPP to 

(i) use the HGDG tool in the attribution of the GPB; 

(ii) closely monitor the implementation of the programs and projects embodied in the GPB and if needed, intervene immediately, if delays in the implementation were observed, amend the GPB, if warranted.

We reiterated and made additional recommendations that the Local Chief Executive:

if budget permits, provide a service vehicle intended only for the Assessor’s Office to facilitate the immediate dissemination and validation of the Notices of Assessment (NoA);  

require the Human Resource Management Officer to assess the available manpower complement of the Assessor’s Office, to determine and provide, if possible, the number of needed personnel in the Department to aid in the fast tracking of the distribution of NoA and information dissemination to Barangays;  

require the Municipal Assessor to set attainable yearly targets in coordination with the Acting Municipal Treasurer and implement the proposed strategies to increase and improve collection and to minimize the deficiency in Basic/SEF collection as mentioned above.

We reiterated our previous year’s recommendations and made additions that the Local Chief Executive: 

consider creating an internal audit unit/services which will oversee the completeness of the documentation of the transactions prior to payment in conjunction with the rules under Local Budget Circular 110 which require the Municipal Accountant to strictly enforce “no processing of disbursements” if with incomplete documentations and approval of required signatories;

require the officials concerned to submit the required documentation of the transactions cited under item a.1.2., a.1.3., and b.1.4.i, for further evaluation as basis for the Audit Team’s subsequent audit action;

henceforth, (i) require certifications of unavailability of funds from the Barangay or Schools requesting for financial assistance, attached to the request for assistance; and 

(ii) prior to payment, comply with the requirements for all transactions as mentioned in item 1.8; 

submit justification on the purchases of bikes granted to selected beneficiaries; 

establish clear-cut guidelines, policies and procedures aligned with Department of Social Welfare and Development (DSWD) Office Circulars as mentioned above; and

  require the MBO to provide adequate funding in support of their operations, for “Aid to Barangays” and “Aid to Schools” so as to facilitate fund transfers to this organizations instead of a dole-out donation.

We reiterated our previous year’s recommendations and the Local Chief Executive agreed to require the:
BAC and BAC-TWG to relentlessly improve the quality and extent of their compliance with the requirements of RA 9184, its IRR and relevant rules and regulations in the Municipality’s procurement process by paying attention on the procurement lapses noted above, to avoid the recurrence thereof in future procurements such as, but not limited to the:
preparation of the Project Procurement Management Plan (PPMP) as basis for the preparation of the Annual Procurement Plan (APP);
furnishing COA with copies of all purchase orders/contracts and all papers relative thereto within five (5) days after the perfection of the contract and sending of notification of the time and date of the scheduled deliveries to the Office of the Auditor pursuant to COA Circular No. 2009-001 and 95-006;
on future similar undertakings on infrastructure projects, conduct complete of detailed engineering prior to the preparation of bid documents in order to assure the viability of infrastructure project;
compliance with the requirements in preparing the Approved Budget for the Contract (ABC), specifically defined under DPWH Department Order No. 197, series 2016;
conduct of materials and items of work testing by the Municipal Engineer or the Project Engineer; and
personnel involved in procurement and All BAC Members to regularly check for updates on procurement and if possible, attend webinars on latest issuances pertaining to procurement and other relevant rules and regulations at least once a year, or as needed, as prescribed under the revised implementing rules and regulations of RA 9184 to keep abreast with the latest issuances and be able to comply with the prescribed requirements accordingly.
We also recommended that the LCE:
in coordination with the BAC, (i) submit the lacking documents of the projects mentioned in Annex C, for further evaluation as basis for the Audit Team’s subsequent audit action; and (ii) prepare an explanation on other deficiencies noted also mentioned in Annex C; and
necessitate the Municipal Accountant to check the completeness of the required supporting documents for every transaction before any payment is made.

We recommended and Management agreed that the LCE instruct the:

MSWDO to 

(i) submit photos of the beneficiaries during the actual distribution of SAP-1 as required by the Guideline; 

(ii) coordinate with concerned Barangays and conduct investigation on the noted individuals dissenting the receipt and incomplete receipt of the assistance as appearing above; 

(iii) on future similar undertakings, arrange payroll list alphabetically with adequate reference numbers for easy referencing and cross-matching with supporting documents; 

(iv) coordinate with DSWD Field Office III on the mismatched list, synchronize the data based on the actual payout made to aid in the posting of accurate data on the DSWD website; and

concerned LGU officials, in coordination with the ABC President, to inform the concerned barangays of the noted deviations as mentioned under item b.1.13 of this memorandum and coordinate efforts to investigate the underlying circumstances on the deviations noted in audit.

