We reiterated our recommendations and Management agreed that the Local Chief Executive:

(a)	require the BAC and BAC-TWG to relentlessly improve the quality and extent of their compliance with the requirements of RA 9184, its IRR and relevant rules and regulations in the Municipality’s procurement process by paying attention on the procurement lapses noted above, to avoid the recurrence thereof in future procurements such as, but not limited to, the:
(i) preparation of Project Procurement Management Plan (PPMP) as basis for the preparation of the Annual Procurement Plan (APP);
(ii) furnishing COA with copies of all purchase orders/contracts and all papers relative thereto within five (5) days after  the  perfection  of the contract and  sending of notification of the time and date of the scheduled deliveries to the Office of the Auditor pursuant to  COA Circular No. 2009-001 and 95-006;
(iii) on future similar undertakings on infrastructure projects, conduct complete detailed engineering prior to the preparation of bid documents in order to assure the viability of infrastructure project;
(iv) compliance with the requirements in preparing the Approved Budget for the Contract (ABC), specifically defined under DPWH Department Order No. 197, series 2016;
(v) conduct of materials and items of work testing by the Municipal Engineer or the Project Engineer; and
(vi) submission of the lacking documents of the projects mentioned above, for further evaluation as basis for the Audit Team’s subsequent audit action;
(b)	consider hiring of additional personnel with knowledge in procurement as mandated by RA 9184, if PS limitation will not be compromised or organize two sets of BAC as allowed under Section 11.1.2. of the 2016 IRR, either according to geographical location of PMO or end-user or implementing units of the Procuring Entity; or nature of procurement, to diversify and complete required procurement documents on time; and
(c)	require personnel involved in procurement and All BAC Members to attend trainings on procurement law and its implementing rules and regulations at least once a year as prescribed under the revised implementing rules and regulations of RA 9184; and
(d)	necessitate the Municipal Accountant to check the completeness of the required supporting documents for every transaction before any payment is made.

We reiterated our previous years’ recommendations and Management agreed that the Local Chief Executive, thru the Acting-MENRO:

a)	continue efforts in the scouting for qualified members to complete the required line up of the Solid Waste Management Board (SWMB);
b)	intensify and sustain the current information drive and awareness campaign among the residents, in coordination with the Barangay and DepEd officials, including private companies/organizations by integrating orientation upon application/renewal of business permits and licenses to achieve a holistic, viable and effective implementation of the solid waste management programs in the Municipality;
c)	exercise strong political will to implement the “no littering” ordinance of the LGU; and
d)	request the Barangays (i) to enhance/adopt the Municipal ordinance pertaining to the “no littering” and other related ordinance of the Municipality; and (ii) without Material Recovery Facility (MRF) to exert effort in locating appropriate MRF or if possible, request other Barangays with MRF for the clustering scheme as allowed under the law.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive require the (a) BAC and BAC-TWG to relentlessly improve the quality and extent of their compliance with the requirements of the RA 9184 and its IRR in the Municipality’s procurement process by paying attention on the procurement lapses noted, to avoid the recurrence thereof in future procurements; 

(b) Acting Municipal Accountant to prepare liquidation reports and either return the excess fund to the source agency immediately upon the completion of the intended project or request from the source the authority to use the remaining funds; 

(c) work in close coordination with the Municipal Health Officer and DILG pertaining to fund transfers on scholarship program for the change of PPAs in order to utilize the funds; 

(d) consider hiring of additional personnel with knowledge in procurement as mandated by RA 9184, if PS limitation will not be compromised; and (e) require personnel involved in procurement and All BAC Members to attend training on procurement law and its implementing rules and regulations at least once a year as prescribed under the revised implementing rules and regulations of RA 9184.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive direct the:

Chief of Hospital, in coordination with CMI Administrator, to (i) advise cashiers to include the charge slip number of the Official Receipt for cross referencing and prepare a policy on how to account for all charge slips issued such as monitoring clients on their payment to the cashier prior to release and provide information to the Acting-Municipal Accountant the total discounts granted and collectibles from clients for proper recording; 

(ii) check the completeness of the serial numbers and note any discrepancy before giving to the issuer; 

(iii) based from other government hospital practices, propose a guideline on how to avoid losses from expiring medicines; 

(iv) prepare demand letter for clients with outstanding balances and strictly follow rules; and 

(v) adhere closely on the requirements of DOH pertaining to segregation of waste; providing dietary services; and visible sign for passers-by to easily recognize the Infirmary; and 

(b) Acting-Municipal Accountant to record discounts granted and receivables from clients based on data to be submitted by the personnel of CMI.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive thru the Acting-MENRO

(a) continue efforts in the scouting of qualified members to complete the required line up of the Solid Waste Management Board (SWMB);

(b) carry on with the linkage already started with the Liga ng mga Barangay in gaining support for the implementation of the ordinance on the proper segregation of reusable or recyclable materials from compostable wastes; 

(c) continue to accelerate efforts in the enforcement of “no segregation, no collection” policy; and 

(d) intensify and sustain the current information drive and awareness campaign among the residents in coordination with the DepEd officials in the Municipality and barangay officials on the implementation of the five basic environmental laws on preserving and protecting the environment required under R.A. No. 9003.
